# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: british-columbia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] While colonial authorities worked to contain the disease among settlers through vaccination and quarantine, fewer measures were taken to protect Indigenous communities.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] As a result, the epidemic continued to spread unchecked in many areas, leading to devastating loss of life and long-lasting demographic, social, and political consequences in what is now British Columbia and the northwestern United States.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Pacific Northwest Indigenous peoples experienced several earlier smallpox epidemics, about once per generation after European contact began in the late 18th century: in the late 1770s, 1801–1803, 1836–1838, and 1853.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Each outbreak is estimated to have killed between 30% and 90% of the Indigenous population.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Fort Victoria, which began as a Hudson's Bay Company fur trading fort, experienced a massive population boom in 1858, when it became the way station for prospectors *en route* to the Fraser Canyon Gold Rush.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By 1862, the population of Victoria had grown from 500 to about 4,000–5,000 colonists.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In addition to the influx of colonists after 1858, there were also several large semi-permanent First Nation camps around Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The largest, known as the "Northern Encampment", had been in place since 1858 and was populated by First Nations from the north coast, namely the Tsimshian, Haida, Tlingit, Heiltsuk, and Kwakwakaʼwakw.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] There were also Songhees villages and other First Nations from nearby areas, including Halkomelem and Wakashan speaking peoples, such as the Sto:lo and Nuu-chah-nulth.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The steamship *Brother Jonathan* arrived at Victoria on 12 March 1862 and left the next day.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 18 March *The Daily British Colonist* reported one passenger had the disease.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By 22 March this second infected person was in the Lower Mainland at New Westminster, having travelled across the Strait of Georgia on the *Otter*.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 24 March another vessel from San Francisco, the *Oregon* arrived with at least one passenger infected with smallpox.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] California was struggling with smallpox at the time, but vaccinations and other preventative measures had kept the death toll relatively low.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In late March, the newspaper *The Daily British Colonist* published the first of several articles calling upon the government to take action, including quarantine and vaccination, to control the spread of smallpox among colonists as well as First Nations people camped near Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By 1 April, about half of the colonists in Victoria had been vaccinated.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On the same day, the first case in a First Nation person was reported.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] It is unclear how large a supply of the smallpox vaccine was available.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some sources stated that there was a shortage of vaccines.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] During May, 3,400 Indians along the lower Fraser River were reportedly vaccinated, as were others, in Puget Sound and the Strait of Georgia.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] These groups avoided many deaths from the epidemic.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Governor James Douglas enlisted Hudson's Bay Company physician Dr.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] John Helmcken to vaccinate the Songhees.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In April, when the outbreak was just starting, Dr.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] John Sebastian Helmcken vaccinated about 500 Songhees.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 29 April the Songhees abandoned their villages and moved to Discovery Island in Haro Strait.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Helmcken's vaccines the Songhees survived the epidemic with few deaths.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Most of the Halkomelem-speaking people of the Lower Mainland were saved due to the vaccination efforts of missionaries.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Catholic Oblate missionary Leon Fouquet and his partner Father Pandosy vaccinated a large number Halkomelem peoples such as the Cowichan Quwutsun, as well as some members of other groups like the Squamish and Shishalh.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Fourquet also sent a large supply of vaccine to Casimir Chirouse at Tulalip.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Chirouse vaccinated most of the Tulalip and Nooksack people.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In August, when smallpox arrived in the Puget Sound area the Tulalip and Nooksack were mostly safe, while other First Nations groups were devastated.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Anglican missionary John Good vaccinated the Snuneymuxw.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some Hudson's Bay Company officials took part in vaccination efforts, such as Hamilton Moffat who vaccinated over 100 First Nations near Fort Rupert, and William Manson who vaccinated "a large number" at Fort Kamloops.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Despite Manson's efforts he reported "violent outbreaks" of smallpox in the Kamloops area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some First Nations attempted to inoculate themselves, although how many and how effective it was is not known.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Little was done to prevent smallpox from spreading to the other First Nations encamped near Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Two missionaries tended to the sick at the Northern Encampment and asked for government assistance.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The colonial police commissioner, Augustus Pemberton, said the colony had no authority to interfere or even help bury the dead.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 28 April, the *Daily British Colonist* called upon the government to "remove...the entire Indian population" from the Victoria area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Pemberton, with Governor Douglas's permission, ordered the Tsimshians to leave within one day, had a gunboat stationed to enforce the order, and placed armed guards around Victoria to prevent First Nations from entering.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Most of the Tsimshians left on 1 May, along with a number of Haida and Tlingit.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] However, during May the epidemic continued to ravage the First Nations still living in the Northern Encampment.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Haida set up a large camp at Cadboro Bay.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In early May, two gunboats arrived; HMS *Grappler* and HMS *Forward*.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 11 May, Police Commissioner Pemberton brought the gunboats and many policemen to Cadboro Bay.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] They forced about 300 First Nations to evacuate in 26 canoes.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] When the Cadboro Bay camp was empty the police went to what remained of the Northern Encampment and burned all the dwellings, leaving about 200 Haidas with no canoes.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] They were taken to San Juan Island where they died at a place today called Smallpox Bay.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Police efforts to drive the First Nations away from Victoria continued through late May, as small groups still remained near Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Reports of First Nations dying of smallpox near Victoria continued into June.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The number of First Nation deaths near Victoria in 1862 is not known, but on 11 June, newspapers reported about 1,000 to 1,200 unburied Northern Indian corpses just west of Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Starting in May 1862, thousands of infected First Nations were evicted from the Victoria area and forced to return to their homes in the north, all along the coast from Nanaimo to the Stikine River in southeast Alaska.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Unlike the region around the Salish Sea the northern coast had less previous exposure to smallpox and no vaccines available.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] As the disease spread Indigenous peoples suffered devastating losses.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] There are no first-hand accounts of the initial stages of the epidemic in the north.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By mid-June Victoria newspapers began receiving reports of the toll the disease was taking.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Pentlatch, Eeksen, and Qualicom peoples were greatly reduced and merged with the K'ómoks (Comox).
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Although a few Shishalh people had been vaccinated the nation as a whole was devastated.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Many Kwakwakaʼwakw lived near Fort Rupert, on northern Vancouver Island.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Over the summer of 1862 various ships reported high death tolls.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The disease reduced the Kwakwakaʼwakw population by over 50%.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Likewise there were harrowing reports about the Heiltsuk people of the Bella Bella area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] On 18 July 1862 the *Daily British Colonist* reported that smallpox had killed about 60% of the Heiltsuk people.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Robert Boyd estimates the Heiltsuk population fell by about 72% due to the epidemic.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Many villages were abandoned and survivors soon moved to the consolidated settlement at Bella Bella.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Large areas of traditional Heiltsuk territory were abandoned.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By 1899 the Heiltsuk population had dropped to 319, almost all at Bella Bella.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Nuxalk people were also decimated by smallpox, with a loss of about 58%, and a similar abandonment of villages and whole regions, with consolidation at Bella Coola.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Haida people suffered the most from the smallpox epidemic.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Haida Gwaii experienced a large amount of village abandonment and consolidation.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] No contemporary accounts describe what happened when the first infected Haida returned, but later reports suggest that smallpox circulated among Haida villages for over a year killing about 72% of the Haida people.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Many historic Haida villages were abandoned in the years following the epidemic, including Ninstints, Kloo, Skedans, Cumshewa, Dadens, Haina, Hiellen, Kung, Klinkwan, and "Old" Kasaan, among others.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Survivors consolidated in four main settlements: Skidegate, Masset, Hydaburg, and "New" Kasaan.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Tsimshian forced away from Victoria brought smallpox to Fort Simpson, whence it spread widely starting in June 1862.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] By early July the First Nations settlement outside the fort was deserted due to deaths and people fleeing the area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Tsimshian settlement at Metlakatla had only just been founded by the missionary William Duncan, who intended it to be a utopian Christian community.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Duncan was able to quarantine Metlakatla by refusing to allow First Nations who showed any signs of smallpox to be admitted.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] His efforts resulted in Metlakatla being mostly spared from the disease.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Duncan also used the epidemic to proselytize, saying that the epidemic had been sent by God as a punishment for the sins of the Tsimshian, and that those who repented and "came to Jesus" and were baptized would be spared.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Duncan also recorded news about the spread of the disease up the Skeena River, and elsewhere, as refugees sought entrance to Metlakatla.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Tlingits driven from Victoria brought smallpox to the Stikine River area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some of the refugees were escorted by the gunboat HMS *Topaz* all the way from Victoria to Russian America.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] No records survive of the situation in the Stikine area during July and August, when the epidemic was likely at its height.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In early September HMS *Devastation* visited the area and noted major population loss and the continuing spread of smallpox.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The epidemic spread north into the Alexander Archipelago but was limited due to an extensive Russian vaccination program.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some Tlingit groups had not been part of the Russian program and these were decimated by the disease, especially the Henya Tlingit of northern Prince of Wales Island.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Mainland Tlingit suffered losses of about 60%, and the Island Tlingit about 37%.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Two-thirds of British Columbia First Nations died—around 20,000 people.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The death rate was highest in southeast Alaska and Haida Gwaii—over 70% among the Haida and 60% among the Tlingit.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Almost all Indigenous nations along the coast, and many in the interior, were devastated, with a death rate of over 50% for the entire coast from Puget Sound to Sitka, Alaska, then part of Russian America.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In some areas the Indigenous population fell by as much as 90%.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The disease was controlled among colonists in 1862 but it continued to spread among Indigenous populations through 1863.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Up until the 1862–1863 epidemic, the colonial authorities acquired Indigenous land through treaties.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Governor James Douglas had signed 14 land cession treaties on Vancouver Island, known as the Douglas Treaties.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In 1864, after the epidemic, the colony's Chief Commissioner of Land and Works Joseph Trutch decided to stop recognizing Aboriginal title and abandon the treaty process.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] This set the precedent of British Columbia taking Indigenous land by fiat rather than treaty.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The large population losses also caused widespread First Nations village abandonment and consolidation, cultural loss, and increased conflict and hostility with colonists.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] In Haida Gwaii, following the 1862 epidemic, over nineteen villages diminished to four by the early 20th century.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Settlers started occupying empty land that Indigenous groups had left following the devastation of the epidemic with hopes of later returning.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some groups resisted encroachment, including the Tsilhqotʼin who resisted when settlers started to build a wagon road through their territory without permission, leading to the Chilcotin War in 1864.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] One of the foremen of the road-building project threatened the Tsilhqotʼin with smallpox.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The war ended with the hanging of six Tsilhqotʼin chiefs.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Some historians have described the epidemic as a deliberate genocide because the Colony of Vancouver Island and the Colony of British Columbia could have prevented the epidemic but chose not to, and in some ways facilitated it.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] While colonial authorities used quarantine, smallpox vaccine, and inoculation to keep the disease from spreading among colonists and settlers, it was largely allowed to spread among Indigenous peoples.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The Colony of Vancouver Island made attempts to save some First Nations, but most were forced to leave the vicinity of Victoria and go back to their homelands, despite awareness that it would result in a major smallpox epidemic among First Nations along the Pacific Northwest coast.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Many colonists and newspapers were vocally in favour of expulsion.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The situation in the Puget Sound region was similar, with newspapers encouraging settlers to get vaccinated, but with little effort towards protecting First Nations.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] Most papers supported removing First Nations.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] The effect of the epidemic in the Puget Sound area is not well documented and it appears it did not spread south beyond the Chehalis people of the Chehalis River area.
[src:british-columbia/1862-pacific-northwest-smallpox-epidemic] At the time, and still today, some First Nations say that the colonial government deliberately spread smallpox for the purpose of stealing their land.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The **2001 British Columbia general election** was the 37th provincial election in the Province of British Columbia, Canada.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] It was held to elect members of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The election was called on April 18, 2001 and held on May 16, 2001.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Voter turnout was 55.4 per cent of all eligible voters.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The incumbent British Columbia New Democratic Party (BC NDP), in office since 1991, had been rocked by two major scandals—the Fast Ferries Scandal and a bribery scandal involving Premier Glen Clark.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] With the NDP's ratings flatlining, Clark resigned in August 1999, and Deputy Premier Dan Miller took over as caretaker premier until Ujjal Dosanjh was elected his permanent successor in February.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Dosanjh was not, however, able to restore the party's public image, and the BC NDP suffered a resounding defeat at the hands of the British Columbia Liberal Party (BC Liberals), led by former Vancouver mayor Gordon Campbell.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The BC Liberals won over 57% of the popular vote, and an unprecedented 77 of the 79 seats in the provincial legislature—the largest victory in the province's electoral history.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The BC NDP, on the other hand, suffered a near-total political collapse.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] The party lost almost half of the share of the popular vote that it had won in the 1996 election, while its seat count fell from 39 seats to only two—those of Deputy Premier and Education Minister Joy MacPhail and Community Development Minister Jenny Kwan.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] It was easily the worst defeat of a sitting government in British Columbia history.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] It was also the fourth worst defeat of a sitting provincial government in Canada, eclipsed only by the New Brunswick election of 1987, the Alberta election of 1935, and the Prince Edward Island election of 1935.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] In each of those elections, the governing party–the New Brunswick Tories, the United Farmers of Alberta and the PEI Tories–was completely wiped off the map.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Dosanjh resigned as party leader soon after the election; he had actually conceded defeat a week before voters went to the polls.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Despite being the only other party in the Assembly, the BC NDP lacked the four seats then required for official party status.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] An Act was passed in 2000 providing for an increase of seats from 75 to 79, upon the next election.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] x – less than 0.005% of the popular vote.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Unity Party results are calculated relative to Family Coalition Party results.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] 2. parties receiving more than 1% of the popular vote, or fielding candidates in at least half of the constituencies, are listed separately.
[src:british-columbia/2001-british-columbia-general-election] Reform is also listed separately, as it was a major contender in 1996, to identify the districts that still nominated candidates.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] The **2005 British Columbia general election** was held on May 17, 2005, to elect members of the Legislative Assembly (MLAs) of the Province of British Columbia (BC), Canada.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] The British Columbia Liberal Party (BC Liberals) formed the government of the province prior to this general election under the leadership of Premier Gordon Campbell.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] The main opposition was the British Columbia New Democratic Party (BC NDP), whose electoral representation was reduced to two MLAs in the previous provincial election in 2001.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] The BC Liberals retained power, with a reduced majority of 46 out of 79 seats, down from the record 77 out of 79 in 2001.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Under amendments to the BC Constitution Act passed in 2001, BC elections are now held on fixed dates: the second Tuesday in May every four years.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] This was the first provincial election for which elector data in the provincial elector list was synchronised with the National Register of Electors.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Coincidental with the general election, BC voters also voted on whether or not to change the province's electoral system.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] The BC electoral reform referendum was held in conjunction with this election.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] This referendum asked voters whether or not they support the proposed electoral reforms of the Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform, which included switching to a single transferable vote (STV) system.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Had it been approved by 60% of voters in 60% of ridings), the new electoral system would have been implemented for the general election in 2009.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Although the proposed reform attracted a clear majority (58% of the popular vote in favour, with 77 out of 79 ridings showing majority support), the level of support was just short of that required for mandatory implementation.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] A new vote on a revamped version of STV was held in conjunction with the 2009 British Columbia general election.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Democratic Reform is highlighted, as it received more votes than the Marijuana Party while having fewer candidates.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Conservatives are also listed separately, as they achieved significant 3rd and 4th places in several districts.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Paul Nettleton was the incumbent Liberal MLA in Prince George-Omineca.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Besides the usual public polling by market research firms, other organizations have been attempting to predict the results of the upcoming election using alternate methods.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Will McMartin at the progressive online newspaper The Tyee makes his predictions by looking at "historic election results and selected demographics, as well as public opinion polls, regional sources and input from Election Central readers" (see details): Seats: Lib 51, NDP 28, Other 0.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] British Columbia has Canada's least restrictive elections laws with regard to political party registration, and consequently there are currently nearly 50 parties registered with Elections BC, by far the most of any jurisdiction in the country.
[src:british-columbia/2005-british-columbia-general-election] Twenty-five parties contested the 2005 election, also a considerably greater number than anywhere else in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] The **2009 British Columbia general election** was held on May 12, 2009, to elect members of the Legislative Assembly in the Canadian province of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] The British Columbia New Democratic Party (BC NDP) under the leadership of Carole James was the Official Opposition.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] The election was the first contested on a new electoral map completed in 2008, with the total number of constituencies increased from 79 in the previous legislature to 85.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Under amendments to the BC Constitution Act passed in 2001, BC elections are now held on fixed dates which are the second Tuesday in May every four years.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] A second referendum on electoral reform was held in conjunction with the election.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] The election did not produce a significant change in the province's political landscape.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] The BC Liberals, who had been in power since the 2001 provincial election, were returned to power, constituting the first time in 23 years a party had won three elections in a row in British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Polling at the start of the year had shown the Liberals on-track to be returned with an increased majority, but a late shift in voter intentions from the Green Party to the NDP would ultimately lead to a near-repeat of the previous election four years prior.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] As a result of the seat redistribution, both the Liberals and the New Democrats gained seats, and both parties increased their popular vote by less than one per cent over 2005.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Each party lost two incumbent MLAs: the BC NDP's Jenn McGinn and Charlie Wyse, and the Liberals' John Nuraney and Wally Oppal were defeated.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] All other seat changes in the election resulted from the new seats or from retiring incumbents.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Voter turnout was 50.99% of eligible voters (1,651,567 registered voters).
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] An Act was passed in 2008 providing for an increase of seats from 79 to 85, upon the next election.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Also taking in part of Maple Ridge-Mission.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Also taking in part of Malahat-Juan de Fuca.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] Also taking in part of Vancouver-Fairview.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] April 10, 2008, passage of *the Electoral Districts Act*, 2008 moving BC from 79 to 85 constituencies.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] October 29, 2008, by-elections in Vancouver-Burrard and Vancouver-Fairview, both won by the New Democrats.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] April 14, 2009, the campaign will officially begin when the writ is issued.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] April 24, 2009 1pm close of nominations for the election.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] There was one TV debate featuring the leaders of the three major parties: Gordon Campbell, Carole James, and Jane Sterk on all three major BC networks on Sunday May 3 at 5:00 p.m.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] CKNW had a debate of the three leaders on April 23 from 8:30 a.m. to 10:00 a.m.
[src:british-columbia/2009-british-columbia-general-election] CBC Radio One had a debate of the three leaders on April 21 at 7:30 a.m.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] It was regarded by the Olympic Committee to be among the most successful Olympic games in history, in both attendance and coverage.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Approximately 2,600 athletes from 82 nations participated in 86 events in fifteen disciplines.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Both the Winter Olympic and Paralympic Games were organized by the Vancouver Organizing Committee (VANOC), headed by John Furlong.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Winter Games were the third Olympics to be hosted by Canada, and the first to be held within the province of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Canada had hosted the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal, Quebec, and the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary, Alberta.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Following Olympic tradition, incumbent Vancouver mayor Sam Sullivan received the Olympic flag during the closing ceremony of the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, Italy.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The flag was raised in a special ceremony on February 28, 2006, and was on display at Vancouver City Hall until the Vancouver opening ceremony.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The event was officially opened by Governor General Michaëlle Jean, accompanied by the Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper and International Olympic Committee (IOC) president Jacques Rogge.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver was selected to host the 2010 Winter Olympics on July 2, 2003, at the 115th IOC Session held in Prague, Czech Republic.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The final host city selection was determined by a secret ballot of the active members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), led by the organization's President, Jacques Rogge.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver secured the hosting rights in the second round of voting, narrowly defeating the bid from Pyeongchang, South Korea, by a margin of 56 to 53 votes, after Salzburg, Austria, was eliminated in the opening round.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver 2010 was immensely successful, with the official Olympic Committee press release citing "Full venues, record public attendance: Over 97% of the 1.54 million tickets available were sold, with 71% to the Canadian public at an average price of $139.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] For the first time, Canada won gold in an official sport as the host nation of the Olympics, having failed to do so in 1976 and 1988 (although Canada won the 1988 woman's curling event in Calgary when it was still only a demonstration sport).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Canada clinched their first gold medal on the second day of the competition, first topping the gold medal tally on the second-to-last day of competition, and went on to become the first host nation since Norway in 1952 to lead the gold medal count.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Canada broke the record for the most gold medals won at a single Winter Olympics (14), which had been set by the Soviet Union in 1976 and Norway in 2002 (13).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The United States won the most medals in total, marking their second time doing so at the Winter Olympics, and broke the record for the most medals won during the Winter Games (37), a record held until then by Germany in 2002 (36).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Athletes from Slovakia and Belarus won the first Winter Olympic gold medals for their nations.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] When Vancouver was bidding for the games, it proposed different dates (5-21 February for the XXI Olympic Winter Games and 5–14 March for the X Paralympic Winter Games).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Shortly afterwards, the Garibaldi Olympic Development Association (GODA) was created in order to prepare a bid to host the Winter Games in the region of Mount Garibaldi, near Whistler.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In 1961, GODA considered developing a bid for the 1968 Winter Games, but the Canadian Olympic Committee (COC) preferred the cities of Calgary and Banff, in Alberta, as the best opportunity for a Canadian bid to succeed.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Calgary's candidacy ultimately failed, and the 1968 Games were awarded to Grenoble.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] A development program for the Whistler and Mount Garibaldi region was then launched to host the 1972 Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] It included the development of road infrastructure, electrical network and drinking water, which was still absent in this region.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] But once again, Banff was chosen to represent Canada as the potential host city for the 1972 Games, which were eventually awarded to Sapporo, Japan.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In 1968, the GODA was finally chosen by the Canadian Olympic Committee with the aim of making a joint candidacy with the city of Vancouver for the organization of the 1976 Winter Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] However, the chances of Vancouver's candidacy dwindled when Montreal was selected to host the 1976 Summer Olympics, and the Vancouver-Garibaldi candidacy was thus eliminated in the first round of voting.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver was again a candidate for the 1980 Games, but withdrew at the last moment.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] For the 1988 Winter Olympics, Calgary was chosen as the preferred site for the Canadian bid, and would go on to win the election and thus become the first Canadian city to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] For the 2010 Games, the Canadian Olympic Association chose Vancouver as the Canadian candidate city over Calgary, which sought to re-host the Games, and Quebec City, which had lost the 2002 Olympic bid in 1995.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On the first round of voting on November 21, 1998, Vancouver-Whistler had 26 votes, Quebec City had 25 and Calgary had 21.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On December 3, 1998, the second and final round of voting occurred between the two leading contenders, which saw Vancouver win with 40 votes compared to Quebec City's 32 votes.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver had also bid for the 1976 games, which were first awarded to Denver, then to Innsbruck and the 1980 games, which were awarded to Lake Placid.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] After the bribery scandal over the candidacy of the Salt Lake City bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics (which resulted in Quebec City asking for compensation (C$8 million) for its unsuccessful bid), many of the rules of the bidding process were changed in 1999.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) created the Evaluation Commission, which was appointed on October 24, 2002.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Prior to the bidding for the 2008 Summer Olympics, host cities would often fly members of the IOC to their city where they toured the city and were provided with gifts.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The lack of oversight and transparency often led to allegations of money for votes.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Afterward, changes brought forth by the IOC bidding rules were tightened, and more focused on technical aspects of candidate cities.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The team analyzed the candidate city features and provided its input back to the IOC.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver won the bid to host the Olympics by a vote of the International Olympic Committee on July 2, 2003, at the 115th IOC Session held in Prague, Czech Republic.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The result was announced by IOC President Jacques Rogge.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver faced two other finalists shortlisted that same February: Pyeongchang, South Korea, and Salzburg, Austria.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Pyeongchang, which later won the rights of hosting both 2018 Winter Olympics and 2024 Winter Youth Olympics (as a part of the Gangwon Province) had the most votes of the three cities in the first round of voting, in which Salzburg was eliminated.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In the run-off, all but two of the members who had voted for Salzburg voted for Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] It was the closest vote by the IOC since Sydney, Australia beat Beijing for the 2000 Summer Olympics by two votes.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver's victory came almost two years after Toronto's 2008 Summer Olympic bid was defeated by Beijing in a landslide vote.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Vancouver Olympic Committee (VANOC) spent C$16.6 million on upgrading facilities at Cypress Mountain, which hosted the freestyle (aerials, moguls, ski cross) and snowboarding events.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] With the opening in February 2009 of the C$40 million Vancouver Olympic/Paralympic Centre at Hillcrest Park, which hosted curling, every sports venue for the 2010 Games was completed on time and at least one year prior to the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] As of mid-2009 it was projected to be C$1.76 billion, mostly raised from non-government sources, primarily through sponsorships and the auction of national broadcasting rights.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] C$580 million was the taxpayer-supported budget to construct or renovate venues throughout Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] A final audit conducted by PricewaterhouseCoopers released in December 2010 revealed total operation cost to have been $1.84 billion and came in on budget resulting in neither surplus nor deficit.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Construction of venues also came on budget with a total cost of $603 million.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The study also said that hosting the Olympics was one of many reasons why the provincial debt grew by $24 billion during the decade.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Indirect Olympic Games costs (e.g. expanded rail network, highways, security, paid time off for government employees "volunteering" etc.) totalled in excess of 7 billion.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In 2011, the provincial auditor-general declined to conduct a post-Games audit.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) also played a role.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] That number was later revealed to be in the region of C$1 billion, an amount in excess of five times what was originally estimated.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Some venues, including the Richmond Olympic Oval, were at sea level, a rarity for the Winter Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Games were also the first—Winter or Summer—to have had an Opening Ceremony held indoors.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Greater Vancouver was the most populous metropolitan area ever to hold the Winter Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In February, the month when the Games were held, Vancouver has an average temperature of 4.8 °C (40.6 °F).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The average temperature as measured at Vancouver International Airport was 7.1 °C (44.8 °F) for the month of February 2010.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The opening and closing ceremonies were held at BC Place Stadium, which received over C$150 million in major renovations.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Competition venues in Greater Vancouver included the Pacific Coliseum, the Vancouver Olympic/Paralympic Centre, the UBC Winter Sports Centre, the Richmond Olympic Oval and Cypress Mountain.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] GM Place, now known as Rogers Arena, played host to ice hockey events, being renamed *Canada Hockey Place* for the duration of the Games since corporate sponsorship is not allowed for an Olympic venue.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Renovations included the removal of advertising from the ice surface and conversion of some seating to accommodate the media.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Winter Olympics marked the first time an Olympic hockey game was played on a rink sized according to NHL rules instead of international specifications.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Competition venues in Whistler included Whistler Creekside at the Whistler Blackcomb ski resort, the Whistler Olympic Park, the Whistler Celebration Plaza and the Whistler Sliding Centre.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Winter Games marked the first time that the energy consumption of the Olympic venues was tracked in real time and made available to the public.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Energy data was collected from the metering and building automation systems of nine of the Olympic venues and was displayed online through the Venue Energy Tracker project.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Olympic Games in Vancouver were broadcast worldwide by a number of television broadcasters.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] As rights for the 2010 Games have been packaged with those for the 2012 Summer Olympics, broadcasters were largely identical for both events.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The host broadcaster was Olympic Broadcasting Services Vancouver, a subsidiary of the IOC's new in-house broadcasting unit Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Olympics marked the first Games where the host broadcasting facilities were provided solely by OBS.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The executive director of Olympic Broadcasting Services Vancouver was Nancy Lee, a former producer and executive for CBC Sports.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The official broadcast theme was a piece called "City of Ice" composed by Rob May and Simon Hill.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In Canada, the Games were the first Olympic Games broadcast by a new Olympic Broadcast Media Consortium led by CTVglobemedia and Rogers Media, displacing previous broadcaster CBC Sports.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Main English-language coverage was shown on the CTV Television Network, while supplementary programming was mainly shown on TSN and Rogers Sportsnet.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Main French-language coverage was shown on V and RDS.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] NBC Universal networks televised the 2010 Winter Olympics in the United States, under a contract in which it paid US$2.2 billion for the rights to the Games and the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Advertising sales had slowed in comparison to previous Olympics due to the ongoing recession, and NBC projected a financial loss upwards of $250 million on the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Due to the growth of social media, NBC faced particular criticism for its traditional practice of tape delaying network coverage of the Olympics for the west coast—a practice that was made more egregious by the fact that these Games took place at sites within the Pacific Time Zone.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In April 2010, the network reported a financial loss of $233 million on the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Associated Press (AP) announced that it would send 120 reporters, photographers, editors and videographers to cover the Games on behalf of the country's news media.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The cost of their Olympics coverage prompted AP to make a "real departure for the wire service's online coverage".
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Rather than simply providing content, it partnered with more than 900 newspapers and broadcasters who split the ad revenue generated from an AP-produced multi-media package of video, photos, statistics, stories and a daily Webcast.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] AP's coverage included a microsite with web widgets facilitating integration with social networking and bookmarking services.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In France, the Games were covered by France Télévisions, which included continuous live coverage on its website.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Olympic Torch Relay is the transfer of the Olympic flame from Ancient Olympia, Greece — where the first Olympic Games were held thousands of years ago — to the stadium of the city hosting the current Olympic Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The flame arrives just in time for the Opening Ceremony.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] For the Vancouver 2010 Olympic Winter Games, the flame was lit in Olympia on October 22, 2009.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] It then traveled from Greece, over the North Pole to Canada's High Arctic and on to the West Coast and Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The relay started its long Canada journey from the British Columbia capital of Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In Canada, the torch traveled approximately 45,000 kilometres (28,000 mi) over 106 days, making it the longest relay route within one country in Olympic history.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Olympic Torch was carried by approximately 12,000 Canadians and reached over 1,000 communities.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] 82 National Olympic Committees (NOC) entered teams in the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Cayman Islands, Colombia, Ghana, Montenegro, Pakistan, Peru and Serbia made their winter Olympic debuts.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Morocco returned to the Winter games after an 18-year absence, and Jamaica and Mexico returned after 8 years.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Seven countries, Costa Rica, Kenya, Luxembourg, Madagascar, Thailand, Venezuela and the Virgin Islands which were at the 2006 Games, did not participate in 2010.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Tonga sought to make its Winter Olympic debut by entering a single competitor in luge, attracting some media attention, but he crashed in the final round of qualifying.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Luxembourg qualified two athletes but did not participate because one did not reach the criteria set by the NOC and the other was injured before the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Philippines also sought to qualify three athletes, one in figure skating pairs and a single one in snowboarding, but failed to make the qualifying standards.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Below is a map of the participating nations and a list of the nations with the number of competitors indicated in brackets.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] 2,626 athletes from 82 NOCs participated in the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The 2010 Winter Olympics featured 86 medal events over 15 disciplines in 7 sports.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The opening and closing ceremonies and the events categorized as ice sports (excluding bobsleigh, luge and skeleton) were held in Vancouver and Richmond.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The sports categorized as "Nordic events" were held in the Callaghan Valley located just to the west of Whistler.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] All alpine skiing events were held on Whistler Mountain (Creekside) and sliding events (bobsleigh, luge and skeleton) were held on Blackcomb Mountain.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Cypress Mountain (located in Cypress Provincial Park in West Vancouver) hosted the freestyle skiing (aerials, moguls and ski cross), and all snowboard events (half-pipe, parallel giant slalom, snowboard cross).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Vancouver 2010 was also the first winter Olympics in which both men's and women's hockey were played on a narrower, NHL-sized ice rink, measuring 200 ft × 85 ft (61 m × 26 m), instead of the international size of 200 ft × 98.5 ft (61.0 m × 30.0 m).
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The games were played at General Motors Place (now Rogers Arena), home of the NHL's Vancouver Canucks, which was temporarily renamed Canada Hockey Place for the duration of the Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Utilizing this existing venue instead of building a new international-sized ice rink facility saved C$10 million in construction costs and allowed an additional 35,000 spectators to attend Olympic hockey games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] However, some European countries expressed concern over this decision, worried that it might give North American players an advantage since they grew up playing on the smaller NHL-sized rinks.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] By contrast, the only other NHL venue to host Olympic hockey, the Calgary Flames' Olympic Saddledome, started construction before Calgary won the bid for the 1988 Winter Olympics and it was designed to accommodate an international ice rink.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] There were a number of events that were proposed to be included in the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On November 28, 2006, the IOC Executive Board at their meeting in Kuwait voted to include ski cross in the official program.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Vancouver Olympic Committee (VANOC) subsequently approved the event to officially be part of the Games program.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The issue over women's ski jumping being excluded ended up in the Supreme Court of British Columbia in Vancouver during April 21–24, 2009, with a verdict on July 10 excluding women's ski jumping from the 2010 Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] A request to appeal that verdict to the Supreme Court of Canada was subsequently denied on December 22 – a decision that marked the end of any hopes that the event would be held during Vancouver 2010.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] To alleviate the exclusion, VANOC organizers invited women from all over Canada to participate at Whistler Olympic Park, including Continental Cup in January 2009.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Women's ski jumping was included in the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi, Russia.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] In the following calendar for the 2010 Winter Olympic Games, each blue box indicates that an event competition, such as a qualification round, was held on that day.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held with the number in these boxes representing the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The top ten listed NOCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The host nation, Canada, is highlighted.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Some in the foreign press, including London 2012 organizers, had criticized the lack of city decorations to acknowledge that Vancouver was the host of the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The original plans to decorate the city in Olympic colours, a tradition followed by other recent Games host cities, were canceled for several reasons.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Besides local opposition, budget cutbacks also forced the organizers to scale back on the elaborate plans.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] VANOC initially benefited from an economic boom and was able to secure lucrative and record domestic sponsorships, but this boom also resulted in rapidly rising construction and labour costs.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Due to these factors, as well as the Great Recession, VANOC built minimalistic functional venues with little aesthetic appeal though they were well-designed for post-Games usage.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] This approach, as well as the fact that most of the infrastructure already existed, meant that the direct costs of the Vancouver Games were much lower than recent Olympic games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Before the Games began and as they commenced, a number of concerns and controversies surfaced and received media attention.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Hours before the opening ceremony, Georgian luger Nodar Kumaritashvili was killed during a training run after being thrown out from his luge, intensifying questions about the safety of the course and prompting organizers to implement quick modifications.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Immediately after the accident, officials attributed it to an athlete error rather than a track deficiency.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The International Luge Federation called an emergency meeting after the accident, and all other training runs were cancelled for the day.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The President of Georgia, Mikheil Saakashvili, thanked the hosts for the way that they handled Kumaritashvili's death which included a moment of silence, bringing his remains back to Georgia and a tribute to him at the opening ceremony.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] One critic questioned the choice of Cypress Mountain as a venue because of its potential lack of snow due to the 2009-10 El Niño.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Because of this possibility, organizers had a contingency plan to truck in snow from Manning Park, about 250 kilometres (160 mi) to the east of the city.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] This allowed events to proceed as planned.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Political decisions involving cancellation of promised low-income housing and the creation of a community of mixed economic backgrounds for post-Games use of the athletes' village was criticized.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Opening ceremonies were stalled while organizers dealt with mechanical problems during the cauldron lighting ceremony.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Speed skating events were delayed due to breakdowns of the ice resurfacers supplied by Olympia, an official sponsor of the Games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Thousands of tickets were voided by organizers when weather conditions made standing-room-only areas unsafe.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Visitors were also upset that, as in past Olympics, medal ceremonies required separate admission and blocks of VIP tickets reserved for sponsors and dignitaries were unused at events.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Other glitches and complaints have included confusion by officials at the start of the February 16 men's and women's biathlon pursuit races, and restricted access to the Olympic flame cauldron on the Vancouver waterfront.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Opposition to the Olympic Games was expressed by activists and politicians, including Lower Mainland mayors Derek Corrigan and Richard Walton.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Many of the public pre-Olympic events held in Vancouver were attended by protesters.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On Saturday, February 13, as part of a week-long Anti-Olympic Convergence, protesters smashed windows of the Downtown Vancouver location of The Hudson's Bay department store.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Protesters later argued that the Hudson's Bay Company, "has been a symbol of colonial oppression for centuries" as well as a major sponsor of the 2010 Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Although the Lil'wat branch of the St'at'imc Nation is a co-host of the Games, a splinter group from the Seton band known as the St'at'imc of Sutikalh, who have also opposed the Cayoosh Ski Resort, feared the Olympics would bring unwanted tourism and real estate sales to their territory.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Local aboriginal people, as well as Canadian Inuit, initially expressed concern over the choice of an inukshuk as the symbol of the Games, with some Inuit leaders such as former Nunavut Commissioner Peter Irniq stating that the inukshuk is a culturally important symbol to them.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] He said that the "Inuit never build inuksuit with head, legs and arms.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] I have seen inuksuit [built] more recently, 100 years maybe by non-Inuit in Nunavut, with head, legs and arms.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On March 11, 2010, it was reported that the Polish cross country skier Kornelia Marek was tested positive for EPO by the Polish Olympic Committee.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] If found guilty of doping by the International Olympic Committee, Marek and the relay teams would be disqualified and stripped of their Vancouver results.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] She would also be banned from the next Winter Olympics in Sochi, Russia, in 2014.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Marek denied taking any banned substances, but the backup "B" sample from the Vancouver doping lab confirmed the "A" sample.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] On October 9, 2017, the IOC announced that three positive doping cases had been found from their re-analysis programme from the 2010 games.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] All three cases belonged to the same athlete, whose identity was not released at the time.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The IOC had re-tested 1,195 urine samples from the games out of the 1,710 taken, which equates to 70%, as part of their re-analysis programme.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Weeks later, the athlete was confirmed to be Slovenian biathlete Teja Gregorin.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The mascots of the 2010 Winter Olympics are a spirit bear named Miga and a Sasquatch named Quatchi.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The massive celebratory crowds in downtown Vancouver were highly praised by the IOC.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Jacques Rogge, the president of IOC, indicated that "the way Vancouver embraced these Games was extraordinary.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] They were also the best watched Winter Olympics since the 1994 Olympics in Lillehammer.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] They are also mentioned alongside the Sydney 2000 Summer games in regards to the best atmosphere.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] A large part is credited to the citizens of Vancouver, British Columbia and Canada.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Some members of the media (mostly, and particularly the British media) criticized the Own the Podium and criticized the celebrations as having been somewhat nationalistic, but this was not an opinion shared by many.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Some suggested that the British media were making these criticisms in order to make the upcoming 2012 Summer Olympics more appealing.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Lord Sebastian Coe, chairman of the 2012 London Olympic Games Organizing Committee, attended the Vancouver Olympics to see how the city coped with the challenges of hosting.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Coe added "Rarely have I seen a host city so passionate and so ready to embrace the Games".
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Vancouver Olympics also organized and hosted the first Pride House for LGBT athletes in the history of the event.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Directly as a result of Canada's medal performance at the 2010 Olympics, the Government of Canada announced in the 2010 federal budget, a new commitment of $34 million over the next two years towards programs for athletes planning to compete in future Olympics.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] This is in addition to the $11 million per year federal government commitment to the Own the Podium program.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Also, as a result of hosting the 2010 Olympics, the British Columbia government pledged to restore funding for sports programs and athlete development to 2008 levels, which amounts to $30 million over three years.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] Unlike at previous Games, all new venues were designed with their post-Games use in mind.
[src:british-columbia/2010-winter-olympics] The Richmond Olympic Oval was converted from a speed skating oval into an indoor multi-sports centre, the Hillcrest Centre is now a multi-purpose community centre with hockey rink and swimming pool and Whistler Olympic Park is used for public recreation, athlete training, and competition events.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The **2013 British Columbia general election** took place on May 14, 2013, to elect the 85 members of the 40th Parliament of British Columbia to the Legislative Assembly in the Canadian province of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The British Columbia Liberal Party (BC Liberals) formed the government during the 39th Parliament prior to this general election, initially under the leadership of Premier Gordon Campbell then after his resignation, Christy Clark.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The British Columbia New Democratic Party (BC NDP) under the leadership of Carole James, and then Adrian Dix, formed the Official Opposition.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The BC Green Party under the leadership of Jane Sterk and the BC Conservative Party under John Cummins were also included in polling, although neither party had representation at the end of the 39th Parliament.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The Liberal Party won its fourth straight majority; Clark was defeated in her riding, but she was re-elected to the legislature in a subsequent by-election in Westside-Kelowna on July 10, 2013, after Liberal MLA Ben Stewart stepped down on her behalf.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The NDP remained the official opposition, losing two seats, and the Green Party won its first-ever seat with future leader Andrew Weaver being elected in the Victoria-area riding of Oak Bay-Gordon Head.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Clark's Liberals had consistently trailed the opposition New Democrats by multiple percentage points in every public opinion poll throughout the campaign.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Even poll results released on the last day of the campaign suggested that the New Democrats had an eight to nine percentage point margin over the Liberals.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Only one pollster, Forum Research, had released a poll which suggested that the Liberals were close enough that a victory was even possible for them, although even that poll had the New Democrats ahead by two percentage points.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The Liberals' upset victory led to significant media debate about the quality of opinion polling in Canadian elections.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Section 23 of British Columbia's *Constitution Act* provides that general elections occur on the second Tuesday in May of the fourth calendar year after the last election.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] As an election was held on May 12, 2009, the next election was scheduled for May 14, 2013.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The same section, though, makes the fixed election date subject to the Lieutenant Governor's right to dissolve the Legislative Assembly as he or she sees fit.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] The writs were dropped April 16, 2013, and the general election was held on May 14, 2013, with advance voting made available on May 8 through 11.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] After leading the BC Liberals for 17 years, Gordon Campbell announced he would resign as Premier and party leader in November 2010.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] This was seen as the result of opposition to the Harmonized Sales Tax, which was very unpopular with voters.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] In the ensuing leadership campaign, Christy Clark, the eventual winner, suggested she would prefer to hold an election earlier than 2013 to secure her own mandate.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] She was believed to be preparing her party for an election as early as autumn 2011.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] However, due to the unfavourable result from the HST referendum, she decided to rule out an early election.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Voter turnout was 57.1 percent, but varied from riding to riding.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] 10 of the 85 ridings had less than 50 percent voter turnout.
[src:british-columbia/2013-british-columbia-general-election] Richmond and Kelowna were the only major cities with under 50 percent turnout.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The **2017 British Columbia general election** was held on May 9, 2017, to elect 87 members (MLAs) to the Legislative Assembly to serve in the 41st Parliament of the Canadian province of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] It was the first election contested on a new electoral map completed in 2015, and the total number of constituencies had increased from 85 to 87.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] New districts were added in Richmond and Surrey, while the boundaries of 48 existing electoral districts were adjusted.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The election saw no party win a majority of seats for the first time since the 1952 election: the Liberals won 43 seats, the NDP won 41 seats and the Greens won three seats.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] From 1952 to 2017, especially in the 2005 to 2017 period, often a single party that had not received a majority of the votes cast had achieved a majority of seats and held power.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] As no one party held a majority of seats, a working majority had to be forged.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] After a period of negotiating, on May 29 Green Party leaders agreed to provide confidence and supply to an NDP government.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Clark meanwhile indicated she would remain in office and seek the confidence of the legislature.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On June 29, the opposition MLAs voted against Clark's speech from the throne, and Lieutenant Governor Judith Guichon, having rejected Clark's request to dissolve parliament, invited NDP leader Horgan to form a government.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On July 18, Horgan became the new premier.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The Greens maintained the NDP government in power, although Weaver and the other Green MLAs did not join the cabinet and were not given any official roles in the government.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The election was notable in that it marked the end of the Liberal majority government that had led the province since the 2001 election, and the first election in Canada at the federal or provincial level that saw more than one member of a Green party elected.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] An act was passed in 2015 providing for an increase of seats from 85 to 87, upon the next election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Parts went to Fraser-Nicola and West Vancouver-Sea to Sky.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] From parts of Surrey-Cloverdale and Surrey-Panorama.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Also taking in part of Richmond-Steveston.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] As an election was held on May 14, 2013, the subsequent election was conducted on May 9, 2017.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The same section, though, makes the fixed election date subject to the Lieutenant Governor's right to dissolve the Legislative Assembly as he or she sees fit (in practice, on the advice of the Premier).
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Advance voter registration ended April 11.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Advance voting was from April 29 to 30, then began again May 3 and lasted until May 6 before the general election on May 9.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] In the 2013 general election, the BC Liberal Party under the leadership of Premier Christy Clark were re-elected with a majority government.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The British Columbia New Democratic Party, under the leadership of Adrian Dix, again formed the Official Opposition with a slightly reduced total of 34 seats.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Despite the victory, Clark was defeated by NDP candidate David Eby in her riding of Vancouver-Point Grey but was later elected in the Westside-Kelowna riding by-election in July 2013 following Ben Stewart's resignation of his seat the previous month so that she could return to the Legislature.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The Green Party, under leader Jane Sterk, won its first seat in the legislature, though Sterk herself was not elected.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Dix resigned as NDP leader following the election and was succeeded by Horgan in the NDP 2014 leadership election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On August 13, 2013, Sterk announced she would resign as Green Party leader; Adam Olsen was appointed interim leader on August 25, 2013.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The Conservative Party, under the leadership of John Cummins, failed to win a seat and Cummins resigned after the Westside-Kelowna by-election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On February 2, 2016, two by-elections occurred in Vancouver-Mount Pleasant and Coquitlam-Burke Mountain to replace Jenny Kwan and Douglas Horne, who had both resigned to seek election in the 2015 Canadian federal election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The *Electoral Districts Act* was updated in November 2015 to establish the new electoral districts, adding one new electoral district in Surrey and one in Richmond.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Additionally, the boundaries of 48 existing electoral districts were adjusted.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] According to Elections BC, each candidate's campaign was permitted spend a maximum of $77,674 over the 28 day election period and each political party, in addition, could spend $4,882,405.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Also, each third party advertiser could spend up to $3,329 in a single electoral district and up to $166,445 overall.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Unlike the Federal government or most provinces, British Columbia has no limits on political donations.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Wealthy individuals, corporations, unions and even foreigners are allowed to donate large amounts to political parties there.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On January 13, 2017, *The New York Times* published a story calling British Columbia the "Wild West" of Canadian political cash.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] *The Globe and Mail* also followed up with a special investigation of "British Columbia: The 'wild west' of fundraising".
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The investigation found that lobbyists are giving tens of thousands of dollars in their own name – and some power brokers are breaking one of the few rules the province has in place.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] With no limits on political donations in BC, the provincial Liberals raised $12.4 million last year – $4.5 million from individuals and $7.9 million from corporations.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On March 5, 2017, Elections BC announced it was launching a probe into Liberal Party fundraising.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The Official Opposition, the NDP, has promised to ban corporate and union donation if elected, as well as limits on individual donations, but continues to accept corporate and union donations at the present time.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] The Green Party announced in September 2016 that it would no longer accept donations from corporations or unions.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] In terms of election spending, British Columbia currently has no spending limits ahead of the election period.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] During the 2009 election period, there was a spending limit of $4.4 million.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Spending limits for the 2017 election period were adjusted for changes to the consumer price index before being confirmed during the second week in April 2017.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Parties receiving more than 1% of the popular vote, or fielding candidates in at least half of the constituencies, are listed separately.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Conservatives are also shown separately, as they had been a significant player in 2013, and Libertarians are noted due to the number of candidates fielded in this election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Alana DeLong was previously a Progressive Conservative member of the Legislative Assembly of Alberta.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On May 9, it was not immediately clear what form the government would take, as Elections BC does not count absentee ballots until two weeks after election day.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] This final count would determine the makeup of the legislature, since several seats were won with margins of a few hundred votes or less, and both the Liberals and NDP hoped to acquire enough seats to secure a majority.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] No seats changed hands, however, after the counting of absentee ballots concluded on May 24, and the initial count of 43–41–3 was confirmed.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] As no single party won a majority of seats, the Green Party was approached by both the Liberals and the NDP to determine whether they would support a minority government or a coalition government headed by either party.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] No grand coalition or agreement between the two large parties, excluding the Greens, was seriously considered.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On May 29, Horgan and Weaver announced that the Greens would provide confidence and supply to an NDP minority government, a position which was endorsed the following day by the members of both caucuses.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] In response, Clark indicated that she would have the legislature sit in the coming weeks and seek its confidence in a Liberal minority government, while acknowledging that she would likely be unsuccessful.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] On June 29, the Liberals were defeated in a confidence vote; Clark then asked Lieutenant Governor Judith Guichon to dissolve the legislature and call a new election.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Guichon refused and instead invited Horgan to form an NDP minority government.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Horgan was sworn into office on July 18.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Student votes are mock elections that run parallel to actual elections, in which students not of voting age participate.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] They are administered by Student Vote Canada.
[src:british-columbia/2017-british-columbia-general-election] Student vote elections are for educational purposes and do not count towards the results.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The first known human inhabitants of the area settled in British Columbia at least 10,000 years ago.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] They include the Coast Salish, Tsilhqotʼin, and Haida peoples, among many others.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] One of the earliest British settlements in the area was Fort Victoria, established in 1843, which gave rise to the city of Victoria, the capital of the Colony of Vancouver Island.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Colony of British Columbia (1858–1866) was subsequently founded by Richard Clement Moody, and by the Royal Engineers, Columbia Detachment, in response to the Fraser Canyon Gold Rush.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Moody selected the site for and founded the mainland colony's capital New Westminster.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The colonies of Vancouver Island and British Columbia were incorporated in 1866, after which Victoria became the united colony's capital.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1871, British Columbia entered Confederation as the sixth province of Canada, in enactment of the *British Columbia Terms of Union*.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia is a diverse and cosmopolitan province, drawing on a plethora of cultural influences from its diasporas of British, European, and Asian Canadians, as well as the Indigenous population.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Though the province's ethnic majority originates from the British Isles, many British Columbians also trace their ancestors to continental Europe, East Asia, and South Asia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Indigenous Canadians constitute about 6 percent of the province's total population.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Christianity is the largest religion in the region, though the majority of the population is non-religious.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] English is the common language of the province, although Punjabi, Mandarin Chinese, and Cantonese also have a large presence in the Metro Vancouver region.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Franco-Columbian community is an officially recognized linguistic minority, and around one percent of British Columbians claim French as their mother tongue.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia is home to at least 34 distinct Indigenous languages.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Major sectors of British Columbia's economy include forestry, mining, filmmaking and video production, tourism, real estate, construction, wholesale, and retail.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Its main exports include lumber and timber, pulp and paper products, copper, coal, and natural gas.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia exhibits high property values and is a significant centre for maritime trade: the Port of Vancouver is the largest port in Canada and the most diversified port in North America.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Although less than 5 percent of British Columbia is arable land, significant agriculture exists in the Fraser Valley and Okanagan due to the warmer climate.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia is home to 45% of all publicly listed companies in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The name of the province was chosen by Queen Victoria, when the Colony of British Columbia (1858–1866), i.e., "the Mainland", became a British colony in 1858.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] It refers to the Columbia District, the British name for the territory drained by the Columbia River, in southeastern British Columbia, which was the namesake of the Columbia Department of the Hudson's Bay Company.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Queen Victoria chose *British* Columbia to distinguish what was the British sector of the Columbia District from the United States' ("American Columbia" or "Southern Columbia"), which became the Oregon Territory on August 8, 1848, as a result of the treaty.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The governments of Canada and British Columbia recognize *Colombie-Britannique* as the French name for the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia is bordered to the west by the Pacific Ocean and the American state of Alaska, to the north by Yukon and the Northwest Territories, to the east by the province of Alberta, and to the south by the American states of Washington, Idaho, and Montana.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The southern border of British Columbia was established by the 1846 Oregon Treaty, although its history is tied with lands as far south as California.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia's land area is 944,735 square kilometres (364,764 sq mi).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia's rugged coastline stretches for more than 27,000 kilometres (17,000 mi), and includes deep, mountainous fjords and about 6,000 islands, most of which are uninhabited.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] It is the only province in Canada that borders the Pacific Ocean.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia's highest mountain is Mount Fairweather; the highest mountain entirely within the province is Mount Waddington.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia is considered to be part of the Pacific Northwest and the Cascadia bioregion, along with the American states of Alaska, Idaho, (western) Montana, Oregon, Washington, and (northern) California.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia's capital city, Victoria, is located on the southeastern tip of Vancouver Island.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Only a narrow strip of Vancouver Island, from Campbell River to Victoria, is significantly populated.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Much of the western part of Vancouver Island and the rest of the coast is covered by temperate rainforest.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The province's most populous city, Vancouver, sits at the confluence of the Fraser River and Georgia Strait in the southwest corner of the mainland, an area commonly known as the Lower Mainland.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By land area, Abbotsford is the province's largest city.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Vanderhoof is near the geographic centre of the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The northern, mostly mountainous, two-thirds of the province is largely unpopulated and undeveloped, except for the area east of the Rockies, where the Peace River Country contains BC's portion of the Canadian Prairies, centred at the city of Dawson Creek.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Coast Mountains and the Inside Passage's many inlets provide some of British Columbia's renowned and spectacular scenery, which forms the backdrop and context for a growing outdoor adventure and ecotourism industry.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] 75 percent of the province is mountainous (more than 1,000 m [3,300 ft] above sea level); 60 percent is forested; and only about 5 percent is arable.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The province's mainland away from the coastal regions is somewhat moderated by the Pacific Ocean.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Terrain ranges from dry inland forests and semi-arid valleys, to the range and canyon districts of the Central and Southern Interior, to boreal forest and subarctic prairie in the Northern Interior.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] High mountain regions both north and south have subalpine flora and subalpine climate.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Okanagan wine area, extending from Vernon to Osoyoos at the Oroville–Osoyoos Border Crossing, is one of several wine and cider-producing regions in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Other wine regions in British Columbia include the Cowichan Valley on Vancouver Island and the Fraser Valley.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Semi-desert grassland is found in large areas of the Interior Plateau, with land uses ranging from ranching at lower altitudes to forestry at higher ones.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Because of the many mountain ranges and rugged coastline, British Columbia's climate varies dramatically across the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Coastal southern British Columbia has a mild and rainy climate influenced by the North Pacific Current.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Most of the region is classified as oceanic, though pockets of warm-summer Mediterranean climate also exist in the far-southern parts of the coast.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Precipitation averages above 1,000 millimetres (39 in) in almost all of the coastal region, and Hucuktlis Lake on Vancouver Island receives an average of 6,903 mm (271.8 in) of rain annually.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The annual mean temperature in the most populated areas of the province is up to 12 °C (54 °F), the mildest anywhere in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Outside of the driest valleys, the Southern and Central Interior generally have a humid continental climate with widely variable precipitation.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] For example, the average daily low in Prince George (roughly in the middle of the province) in January is −12 °C (10 °F).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Small towns in the southern interior with high elevation such as Princeton are typically colder and snowier than cities in the valleys.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Heavy snowfall occurs in all elevated mountainous terrain providing bases for skiers in both south and central British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Annual snowfall on highway mountain passes in the southern interior rivals some of the snowiest cities in Canada, and freezing rain and fog are sometimes present on such roads as well.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This can result in hazardous driving conditions, as people are usually travelling between warmer areas such as Vancouver or Kamloops, and may be unaware that the conditions may be slippery and cold.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Winters are generally severe in the Northern Interior which is generally in the subarctic climate zone, but even there, milder air can penetrate far inland.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The coldest temperature in British Columbia was recorded in Smith River, where it dropped to −58.9 °C (−74.0 °F) on January 31, 1947, one of the coldest readings recorded anywhere in North America.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Atlin in the province's far northwest, along with the adjoining Southern Lakes region of Yukon, get midwinter thaws caused by the Chinook effect, which is also common (and much warmer) in more southerly parts of the Interior.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] During winter on the coast, rainfall, sometimes relentless heavy rain, dominates because of consistent barrages of cyclonic low-pressure systems from the North Pacific.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Arctic outflow winds can occasionally result in wind chill temperatures at or even below −17.8 °C (0.0 °F).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] While winters are very wet, coastal areas are generally milder and dry during summer under the influence of stable anti-cyclonic high pressure.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Southern Interior valleys are hot in summer; for example, in Osoyoos, the July maximum temperature averages 31.7 °C (89.1 °F), making it the hottest month of any location in Canada; this hot weather sometimes spreads towards the coast or to the far north of the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Temperatures often exceed 40 °C (104 °F) in the lower elevations of valleys in the Interior during mid-summer, with the record high of 49.6 °C (121.3 °F) being held in Lytton on June 29, 2021, during a record-breaking heat wave that year.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The extended summer dryness often creates conditions that spark forest fires, from dry-lightning or man-made causes.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Many areas of the province are often covered by a blanket of heavy cloud and low fog during the winter months, in contrast to abundant summer sunshine.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Annual sunshine hours vary from 2200 near Cranbrook and Victoria to less than 1300 in Prince Rupert, on the North Coast just south of Southeast Alaska.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The exception to British Columbia's wet and cloudy winters is during the El Niño phase.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] During El Niño events, the jet stream is much farther south across North America, making the province's winters milder and drier than normal.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Winters are much wetter and cooler during the opposite phase, La Niña.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] There are 14 designations of parks and protected areas in the province that reflect the different administration and creation of these areas in a modern context.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] There are 141 ecological reserves, 35 provincial marine parks, 7 provincial heritage sites, 6 National Historic Sites of Canada, 4 national parks and 3 national park reserves.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] 12.5 percent of the province's area (114,000 km2 or 44,000 sq mi) is considered protected under one of the 14 different designations that includes over 800 distinct areas.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia contains a large number of provincial parks, run by BC Parks under the aegis of the Ministry of Environment.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia's provincial parks system is the second largest parks system in Canada, the largest being Canada's National Parks system.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Another tier of parks in British Columbia are regional parks, which are maintained and run by the province's regional districts.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Ministry of Forests operates forest recreation sites.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In addition to these areas, over 47,000 square kilometres (18,000 sq mi) of arable land are protected by the Agricultural Land Reserve.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Much of the province is undeveloped, so populations of many mammalian species that have become rare in much of the United States still flourish in British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Watching animals of various sorts, including a very wide range of birds, has long been popular.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Smaller birds (robins, jays, grosbeaks, chickadees, and so on) also abound.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Murrelets are known from Frederick Island, a small island off the coast of Haida Gwaii.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Many healthy populations of fish are present, including salmonids such as several species of salmon, trout, steelhead, and char.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Besides salmon and trout, sport-fishers in BC also catch halibut, bass, and sturgeon.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] On the coast, harbour seals and river otters are common.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Cetacean species native to the coast include the orca, humpback whale, grey whale, harbour porpoise, Dall's porpoise, Pacific white-sided dolphin and minke whale.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Some endangered species in British Columbia are: Vancouver Island marmot, spotted owl, American white pelican, and badgers.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] White spruce or Engelmann spruce and their hybrids occur in 12 of the 14 biogeoclimatic zones of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] First Nations peoples of British Columbia used plants for food, and to produce material goods like fuel and building products.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Plant foods included berries, and roots like camas.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The area now known as British Columbia is home to First Nations groups with several indigenous languages.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] There are more than 200 First Nations in BC.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Prior to contact (with non-Aboriginal people), human history is known from oral histories, archaeological investigations, and from early records from explorers encountering societies early in the period.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The arrival of Paleoindians from Beringia took place between 20,000 and 12,000 years ago.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Hunter-gatherer families were the main social structure from 10,000 to 5,000 years ago.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The nomadic population lived in non-permanent structures foraging for nuts, berries and edible roots while hunting and trapping larger and small game for food and furs.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Around 5,000 years ago individual groups started to focus on resources available to them locally.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Coast Salish peoples had complex land management practices linked to ecosystem health and resilience.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Forest gardens on Canada's northwest coast included crabapple, hazelnut, cranberry, wild plum, and wild cherry species.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Thus with the passage of time there is a pattern of increasing regional generalization with a more sedentary lifestyle.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] These indigenous populations evolved over the next 5,000 years across a large area into many groups with shared traditions and customs.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] To the northwest of the province are the peoples of the Na-Dene languages, which include the Athapaskan-speaking peoples and the Tlingit, who live on the islands of southern Alaska and northern British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Na-Dene language group is believed to be linked to the Yeniseian languages of Siberia: the Dene of the western Arctic may represent a distinct wave of migration from Asia to North America.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Interior of British Columbia is home to the Salishan language groups such as the Shuswap (Secwepemc), Okanagan and Athabaskan language groups, primarily the Dakelh (Carrier) and the Tsilhqotʼin.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The inlets and valleys of the British Columbia coast shelter large, distinctive populations, such as the Haida, Kwakwakaʼwakw and Nuu-chah-nulth, sustained by the region's abundant salmon and shellfish.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] These peoples developed complex cultures dependent on the western red cedar that included wooden houses, seagoing whaling and war canoes and elaborately carved potlatch items and totem poles.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Contact with Europeans brought a series of devastating epidemics of diseases the people had no immunity to.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The population dramatically collapsed, culminating in the 1862 smallpox outbreak in Victoria that spread throughout the coast.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] European settlement did not bode well for the remaining native population of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Colonial officials deemed colonists could make better use of the land than the First Nations people, and thus the land should be owned by the colonists.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] To ensure colonists would be able to settle properly and make use of the land, First Nations were forcibly relocated onto reserves, which were often too small to support their way of life.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By the 1930s, British Columbia had over 1500 reserves.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Lands now known as British Columbia were added to the British Empire during the 19th century.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Colonies originally begun with the support of the Hudson's Bay Company (Vancouver Island, the mainland) were amalgamated, then entered Confederation as British Columbia in 1871 as part of the Dominion of Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] During the 1770s, smallpox killed at least 30 percent of the Pacific Northwest First Nations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This devastating epidemic was the first in a series; the 1862 Pacific Northwest smallpox epidemic killed about half to two-thirds of the native population of what became British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The arrival of Europeans began around the mid-18th century, as fur traders entered the area to harvest sea otters.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] While it is thought Francis Drake may have explored the British Columbian coast in 1579, it was Juan Pérez who completed the first documented voyage, which took place in 1774.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Juan Francisco de la Bodega y Quadra explored the coast in 1775.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In doing so, Pérez and Quadra reasserted the Spanish claim for the Pacific coast, first made by Vasco Núñez de Balboa in 1513.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The explorations of James Cook in 1778 and George Vancouver in 1792 and 1793 established British jurisdiction over the coastal area north and west of the Columbia River.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1793, Alexander Mackenzie was the first European to journey across North America overland to the Pacific Ocean, inscribing a stone marking his accomplishment on the shoreline of Dean Channel near Bella Coola.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] His expedition theoretically established British sovereignty inland, and a succession of other fur company explorers charted the maze of rivers and mountain ranges between the Canadian Prairies and the Pacific.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Mackenzie and other explorers—notably John Finlay, Simon Fraser, Samuel Black, and David Thompson—were primarily concerned with extending the fur trade, rather than political considerations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1794, by the third of a series of agreements known as the Nootka Conventions, Spain conceded its claims of exclusivity in the Pacific.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This opened the way for formal claims and colonization by other powers, including Britain, but because of the Napoleonic Wars, there was little British action on its claims in the region until later.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The establishment of trading posts by the North West Company and the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC), effectively established a permanent British presence in the region.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Columbia District was broadly defined as being south of 54°40′ north latitude, (the southern limit of Russian America), north of Mexican-controlled California, and west of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] It was, by the Anglo-American Convention of 1818, under the "joint occupancy and use" of citizens of the United States and subjects of Britain.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This co-occupancy was ended with the Oregon Treaty of 1846.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The major supply route was the York Factory Express between Hudson Bay and Fort Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Some of the early outposts grew into settlements, communities and cities.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Among the places in British Columbia that began as fur trading posts are Fort St.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Fur company posts that became cities in what is now the United States include Vancouver, Washington (Fort Vancouver), formerly the "capital" of Hudson's Bay operations in the Columbia District, Colville and Walla Walla (old Fort Nez Percés).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] With the amalgamation of the two fur trading companies in 1821, modern-day British Columbia existed in three fur-trading departments.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The bulk of the central and northern interior was organized into the New Caledonia district, administered from Fort St.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The interior south of the Thompson River watershed and north of the Columbia was organized into the Columbia District, administered from Fort Vancouver on the lower Columbia River.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The northeast corner of the province east of the Rockies, known as the Peace River Block, was attached to the much larger Athabasca District, headquartered in Fort Chipewyan, in present-day Alberta.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Until 1849, these Pacific Slope districts were unorganized territory within British North America.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] While operating under the de facto jurisdiction of HBC administrators, the region—unlike Rupert's Land to the north and east—was never a corporate concession.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Instead, the company merely held a monopoly to trade with the First Nations inhabitants.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This status quo was disrupted by the westward expansion of American exploration and overlapping claims of territorial sovereignty, particularly in the southern Columbia Basin across present-day Washington and Oregon.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1846, the Oregon Treaty divided the territory along the 49th parallel to the Strait of Georgia, with the area south of this boundary (excluding Vancouver Island and the Gulf Islands) transferred to sole American sovereignty.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Colony of Vancouver Island was created in 1849, with Victoria designated as the capital.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] New Caledonia, as the whole of the mainland rather than just its north-central Interior came to be called, continued to be an unorganized territory of British North America, "administered" by individual HBC trading post managers.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] With the Fraser Canyon Gold Rush in 1858, an influx of Americans into New Caledonia prompted the colonial office to designate the mainland as the Colony of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Moody and his family arrived in British Columbia in December 1858.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] He was sworn in as the first lieutenant governor of British Columbia and appointed Chief Commissioner of Lands and Works for British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] On the advice of Lytton, Moody hired Robert Burnaby as his personal secretary.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In British Columbia, Moody "wanted to build a city of beauty in the wilderness" and planned his city as an iconic visual metaphor for British dominance, "styled and located with the objective of reinforcing the authority of the crown and of the robe".
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Subsequent to the enactment of the *Pre-emption Act* of 1860, Moody settled the Lower Mainland.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] He selected the site and founded the new capital, New Westminster.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] He selected the site due to the strategic excellence of its position and the quality of its port.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Moody and the Royal Engineers also built an extensive road network, including what would become Kingsway, connecting New Westminster to False Creek, the North Road between Port Moody and New Westminster, and the Cariboo Road and Stanley Park.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] He named Burnaby Lake after his private secretary Robert Burnaby and named Port Coquitlam's 400-foot "Mary Hill" after his wife.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] As part of the surveying effort, several tracts were designated "government reserves", which included Stanley Park as a military reserve (a strategic location in case of an American invasion).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The *Pre-emption Act* did not specify conditions for distributing the land, so large parcels were snapped up by speculators, including 1,518 hectares (3,750 acres) by Moody himself.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] For this he was criticized by local newspapermen for land grabbing.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Moody designed the first coat of arms of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] It was established at the end of a trail that connected New Westminster with Burrard Inlet to defend New Westminster from potential attack from the US.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By 1862, the Cariboo Gold Rush, attracting an additional 5000 miners, was underway, and Douglas hastened construction of the Great North Road (commonly known now as the Cariboo Wagon Road) up the Fraser Canyon to the prospecting region around Barkerville.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By the time of this gold rush, the character of the colony was changing, as a more stable population of British colonists settled in the region, establishing businesses, opening sawmills, and engaging in fishing and agriculture.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] A series of petitions requesting an assembly were ignored by Douglas and the colonial office until Douglas was eased out of office in 1864.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Finally, the colony would have both an assembly and a resident governor.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Confederation League led the chorus pressing for the colony to join Canada, which in 1867 had been created out of three British North American colonies (the Province of Canada, Nova Scotia and New Brunswick), making up four provinces.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] With the agreement by the Canadian government to extend the Canadian Pacific Railway to British Columbia and assume the colony's debt, British Columbia became the sixth province to join Confederation on July 20, 1871.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The Treaty of Washington sent the "Pig War", a San Juan Islands border dispute, to arbitration in 1871.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1903, the province's territory shrank again after the Alaska boundary dispute settled the vague boundary of the Alaska Panhandle.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Population in British Columbia expanded as mining, forestry, agriculture, and fishing developed.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Mining activity was notable throughout the Mainland, so a common epithet for it, even after provincehood, was "the Gold Colony".
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Agriculture attracted settlers to the fertile Fraser Valley.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Cattle ranchers and later fruit growers came to the drier grasslands of the Thompson Rivers, the Cariboo, the Chilcotin, and the Okanagan.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Forestry drew workers to the temperate rainforests of the coast, which was also the locus of a growing fishery.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The completion of the railway in 1885 contributed to the economy, facilitating the transportation of the region's considerable resources to the east.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The milltown of Granville, also known as Gastown was selected as the terminus.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This prompted the incorporation of the city of Vancouver in 1886.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The completion of the Port of Vancouver spurred rapid growth, and in less than fifty years the city surpassed Winnipeg, Manitoba, as the largest in Western Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The early decades of the province were ones in which issues of land use—specifically, its settlement and development—were paramount.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This included expropriation from First Nations people of their land, control over its resources, as well as the ability to trade in some resources, such as fishing.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Establishing a labour force to develop the province was problematic, and British Columbia was a destination of immigration from Europe, China, Japan and India.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The influx of a non-European population stimulated resentment from the dominant ethnic groups, resulting in agitation and an attempt to restrict the ability of Asian people to immigrate to British Columbia through the imposition of the Chinese head tax.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This resentment culminated in mob attacks against Chinese and Japanese immigrants in Vancouver in 1887 and 1907.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In World War I, the province responded strongly to the call to assist the British Empire against its German foes in French and Belgian battlefields.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] About 55,570 of the province's 400,000 residents, the highest per-capita rate in Canada, responded to the military's need.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] About 6,225 men from the province died in combat.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 1914, a second transcontinental rail line, the Grand Trunk Pacific, was completed.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This opened up the North Coast and Bulkley Valley region to new economic opportunities.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] What had previously been an almost exclusively fur-trading and subsistence economy soon became an area for forestry, farming, and mining.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This sector attracted workers from Asia and Europe, leading to a diverse but conflict-ridden society.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The early 20th century saw significant interaction between immigrants, First Nations, and economic forces.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] There was a rise in the labour movement, marked by strikes and conflicts such as the 1935 docker's strike at Ballantyne Pier and the On-to-Ottawa Trek.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] These events underscored tensions between workers and big business, often mediated by the Communist Party.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Racial and ethnic relations were strained, with legislation reflecting the era's racial prejudices, notably against Asian immigrants and First Nations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The early and mid-20th century was marred by incidents like the Komagata Maru incident, highlighting anti-Asian sentiment.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The interwar period and World War II introduced significant changes, including prohibition and its eventual repeal, and the internment of Japanese Canadians.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The post-war era saw coalition governments and a booming economy, spearheaded by infrastructure projects and industrial expansion.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Bennett, dominated BC politics, initiating major projects and laying the groundwork for future economic growth.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The 1970s and 1980s brought economic challenges and political shifts, culminating in the Expo 86 world's fair and the end of Social Credit dominance.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] This period also saw significant social movements, such as Operation Solidarity.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] There was a transition to New Democratic Party governance in the 1990s, focusing on environmental conservation and economic struggles.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In its second term especially, the NDP government faced political scandals, such as the fast ferry scandal, that ultimately contributed to its downfall.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In the 2001 provincial election, Gordon Campbell's Liberals defeated the NDP, gaining 77 out of 79 total seats in the provincial legislature.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Campbell instituted reforms and removed some of the NDP's policies, along with selling off the previous government's "fast ferries", lowering income taxes, and instituting the controversial long-term lease of BC Rail to Canadian National Railway.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Campbell led his party to victory in the 2005 provincial election against a substantially strengthened NDP opposition and won a third term in the 2009 provincial election.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The province won a bid to host the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 2003, Vancouver's residents had voted in a referendum accepting the responsibilities of the host city should it win its bid.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] 64 percent of residents voted in favour of hosting.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] After the Olympic joy faded, Campbell's popularity fell.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] His management style, implementation of the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) despite election promises not to introduce it, and cancellation of the BC Rail corruption trial led to low approval ratings and loss of caucus support: he resigned in November 2010.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In early 2011, former deputy premier Christy Clark became leader of the Liberals.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Early Clark government actions included raising the minimum wage, creating a new statutory holiday in February called "Family Day", and pushing the development of BC's liquefied natural gas industry.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In the lead-up to the 2013 election, the Liberals lagged behind the NDP by a double-digit gap in the polls but were able to achieve a surprise victory, winning a majority and making Clark the first woman to lead a party to victory in BC.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Her government went on to balance the budget, implement changes to liquor laws and continue with the question of the proposed Enbridge Northern Gateway Pipelines.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In the 2017 election, the NDP formed a minority government with the support of the Green Party through a confidence and supply agreement.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In July 2017, NDP leader John Horgan was sworn in as a premier.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Clark resigned and Andrew Wilkinson became leader of the BC Liberals.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In the 2020 British Columbia general election, the NDP won 57 seats and formed a majority government.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Wilkinson resigned as the leader of the BC Liberals.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] British Columbia has been significantly affected by demographic changes within Canada and around the world.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Vancouver was a major destination for many immigrants from Hong Kong who left the former UK colony prior to its handover to China.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Trends of urbanization mean the Greater Vancouver area now includes 51 percent of the province's population, followed by Greater Victoria with 8 percent.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] These two metropolitan regions have dominated the demographics of BC.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By 2018, housing prices in Vancouver were the second-least affordable in the world.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Many experts point to evidence of money-laundering from China as a contributing factor.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The high price of residential real estate has led to the implementation of an empty homes tax, a housing speculation and vacancy tax, and a foreign buyers' tax on housing.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] The net number of people coming to BC from other provinces in 2016 was almost four times larger than in 2012 and BC was the largest net recipient of interprovincial migrants in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] In 2023, British Columbia experienced a net population loss of 8,624; a substantial percentage of which were people who moved to Alberta.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] By 2021, the COVID-19 pandemic had had a major effect on the province, with over 2,000 deaths and 250,000 confirmed cases.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] However, the COVID-19 vaccine reduced the spread, with 78 percent of people in BC over the age of five having been fully vaccinated.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Also in 2021 but unrelated to COVID-19, the unmarked gravesites of hundreds of Indigenous children were discovered at three former Indian residential schools (Kamloops, St.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p01] Wildfires in 2023 burned nearly 3,000,000 hectares (7,400,000 acres) and incurred a cost of more than a billion dollars.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Statistics Canada's 2021 Canadian census recorded a population of 5,000,879 — making British Columbia Canada's third-most populous province after Ontario and Quebec.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The metropolitan area also includes nine First Nations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The metropolitan area also includes several Indian reserves (the governments of which are not part of the regional district).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Almost half of the Vancouver Island population is in Greater Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is the most diverse province in Canada; as of 2021, the province had the highest proportion of visible minorities in the country.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The five largest pan-ethnic groups in the province are Europeans (60 percent), East Asians (14 percent), South Asians (10 percent), Indigenous (6 percent) and Southeast Asians (5 percent).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2021, 34.4 percent of the population consisted of visible minorities and 5.9 percent of the population was Indigenous, mostly of First Nations and Métis descent.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The question on knowledge of languages allows for multiple responses.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Of the 4,648,055 population counted by the 2016 census, 4,598,415 people completed the section about language.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Of these, 4,494,995 gave singular responses to the question regarding their first language.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] While these languages all reflect the last centuries of colonialism and recent immigration, British Columbia is home to 34 Indigenous languages.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] They are spoken by about 6000 people in total, with 4000 people fluent in their Indigenous languages.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] BC's economy is diverse, with service-producing industries accounting for the largest portion of the province's GDP.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It is the terminus of two transcontinental railways, and the site of 27 major marine cargo and passenger terminals.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Though less than 5 percent of its vast 944,735 square kilometres (364,764 sq mi) land is arable, the province is agriculturally rich (particularly in the Fraser and Okanagan valleys), because of milder weather near the coast and in certain sheltered southern valleys.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Its climate encourages outdoor recreation and tourism, though its economic mainstay has long been resource extraction, principally logging, farming, and mining.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Vancouver, the province's largest city, serves as the headquarters of many western-based natural resource companies.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It also benefits from a strong housing market and a per capita income well above the national average.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] While the coast of British Columbia and some valleys in the south-central part of the province have mild weather, the majority of its land mass experiences a cold-winter-temperate climate similar to the rest of Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Northern Interior region has a subarctic climate with very cold winters.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The climate of Vancouver is by far the mildest winter climate of the major Canadian cities, with nighttime January temperatures averaging above the freezing point.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia has a history of being a resource dominated economy, centred on the forestry industry but also with fluctuating importance in mining.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Employment in the resource sector has fallen steadily as a percentage of employment, and new jobs are mostly in the construction and retail/service sectors.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It now has the highest percentage of service industry jobs in the west, constituting 72 percent of industry (compared to 60 percent Western Canadian average).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The largest section of this employment is in finance, insurance, real estate and corporate management; however, many areas outside of metropolitan areas are still heavily reliant on resource extraction.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] With its film industry known as Hollywood North, the Vancouver region is the third-largest feature film production location in North America, after Los Angeles and New York City.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The economic history of British Columbia is replete with tales of dramatic upswings and downswings, and this boom and bust pattern has influenced the politics, culture and business climate of the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Economic activity related to mining in particular has widely fluctuated with changes in commodity prices over time, with documented costs to community health.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2020, British Columbia had the third-largest GDP in Canada, with a GDP of $309 billion and a GDP per capita of $60,090.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia's debt-to-GDP ratio is edging up to 15.0 percent in fiscal year 2019–20, and it is expected to reach 16.1 percent by 2021–22.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia's economy experienced strong growth in recent years with a total growth rate of 9.6% from 2017 to 2021, a growth rate that was second in the country.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The lieutenant governor, Wendy Lisogar-Cocchia, is the Crown's representative in the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] During the absence of the lieutenant governor, the Governor in Council (federal Cabinet) may appoint an administrator to execute the duties of the office.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] This is usually the chief justice of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is divided into *regional districts* as a means to better enable municipalities and rural areas to work together at a regional level.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia has a 93-member elected legislative assembly, elected by the plurality voting system, though from 2003 to 2009 there was significant debate about switching to a single transferable vote system called BC-STV.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The government of the day appoints ministers for various portfolios, what are officially part of the Executive Council, of whom the province's premier is chair.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The province is currently governed by the British Columbia New Democratic Party (BC NDP) under Premier David Eby.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The 2017 provincial election saw the Liberal Party take 43 seats, the NDP take 41, and the British Columbia Green Party take 3.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] No party met the minimum of 44 seats for a majority, therefore leading to the first minority government since 1953.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Following the election, the Greens entered into negotiations with both the Liberals and NDP, eventually announcing they would support an NDP minority government.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Previously, the right-of-centre British Columbia Liberal Party governed the province for 16 years between 2001 and 2017, and won the largest landslide election in British Columbia history in 2001, with 77 of 79 seats.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The legislature became more evenly divided between the Liberals and NDP following the 2005 (46 Liberal seats of 79) and 2009 (49 Liberal seats of 85) provincial elections.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The NDP and its predecessor the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) have been the main opposition force to right-wing parties since the 1930s and have governed with majority governments in 1972–1975, 1991–2001 and since 2020 (with a minority government from 2017 to 2020).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Green Party plays a larger role in the politics of British Columbia than Green parties do in most other jurisdictions in Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] After a breakthrough election in 2001 (12.39 percent), the party's vote share declined (2005 – 9.17 percent, 2009 – 8.09 percent, 2013 – 8.13 percent) before increasing again to a record high of 16.84 percent at the 2017 election.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The British Columbia Liberal Party is not related to the federal Liberal Party and does not share the same ideology.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Instead, the BC Liberal party is a rather diverse coalition, made up of the remnants of the Social Credit Party, many federal Liberals, federal Conservatives, and those who would otherwise support right-of-centre or free enterprise parties.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2022, Kevin Falcon was elected leader of the BC Liberals, promising to rename the party in an effort to distance themselves from their federal counterparts.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2023, the party rebranded as BC United.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Historically, there have commonly been third parties present in the legislature (including the Liberals themselves from 1952 to 1975); the BC Green Party is the current third party in British Columbia, with three seats in the legislature.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Prior to the rise of the Liberal Party, British Columbia's main political party was the BC Social Credit Party, which governed the province for 20 years.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] While sharing some ideology with the subsequent Liberal government, they were more right-wing, although they undertook nationalization of various important monopolies, notably BC Hydro and BC Ferries.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is known for having politically active labour unions who have traditionally supported the NDP or its predecessor, the CCF.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia's political history is typified by scandal and a cast of colourful characters, beginning with various colonial-era land scandals and abuses of power by early officials (such as those that led to McGowan's War in 1858–59).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Notable scandals in Social Credit years included the Robert Bonner Affair and the Fantasy Gardens scandal which forced Premier Bill Vander Zalm to resign and ended the Social Credit era.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] NDP scandals included Bingogate, which brought down NDP Premier Mike Harcourt, and the alleged scandal named Casinogate which drove NDP Premier Glen Clark to resign.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A variety of scandals plagued the 2001–2017 Liberal government, including Premier Gordon Campbell's arrest for drunk driving in Maui and the resignation of various cabinet ministers because of conflict-of-interest allegations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A raid on the Parliament Buildings on December 28, 2003, in Victoria, including the Premier's Office, resulted in charges only for ministerial aides, although key cabinet members from the time resigned.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Campbell eventually resigned in late 2010 due to opposition to his government's plan to introduce a Harmonized Sales Tax (HST) and was replaced by Christy Clark as premier in the 2011 BC Liberal leadership election.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is underrepresented in the Senate of Canada, leading Premier Christy Clark to refuse to cooperate with the federal government's reforms for senate appointments to be made based on the recommendations of an advisory board that would use non-partisan criteria.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Hours after that plan was unveiled in Ottawa on December 3, 2015, Clark issued a statement that it did "not address what's been wrong with the Senate since the beginning".
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The imbalance in representation in that House is apparent when considering population size.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The six senators from BC constitute only one for every 775,000 people vs. one for every 75,000 in Prince Edward Island, which has four senators.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Nova Scotia and New Brunswick have much smaller populations than BC, yet each has ten senators according to a Global News summary.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Correcting this imbalance would require a constitutional amendment, but that is unlikely to be supported by the Atlantic provinces.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Transportation played a huge role in British Columbia's history.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Rocky Mountains and the ranges west of them constituted a significant obstacle to overland travel until the completion of the transcontinental railway in 1885.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Peace River Canyon through the Rocky Mountains was the route the earliest explorers and fur traders used.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Fur trade routes were only marginally used for access to British Columbia through the mountains.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Travel from the rest of Canada before 1885 meant the difficulty of overland travel via the United States, around Cape Horn or overseas from Asia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Nearly all travel and freight to and from the region occurred via the Pacific Ocean, primarily through the ports of Victoria and New Westminster.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Until the 1930s, rail was the only means of overland travel to and from the rest of Canada; travellers using motor vehicles needed to journey through the United States.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] With the construction of the Inter-Provincial Highway in 1932 (now known as the Crowsnest Pass Highway), and later the Trans-Canada Highway, road transportation evolved into the preferred mode of overland travel to and from the rest of the country.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] As of 2021, the number of electric vehicles sold in British Columbia (as a percentage of total vehicle sales) was the highest of any Canadian province or US state.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Because of its size and rugged, varying topography, British Columbia requires thousands of kilometres of provincial highways to connect its communities.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia's roads systems were notoriously poorly maintained and dangerous until a concentrated program of improvement was initiated in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] There are now freeways in Greater Victoria, the Lower Mainland, and Central Interior of the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Much of the rest of the province, where traffic volumes are generally low, is accessible by well-maintained generally high-mobility two-lane arterial highways with additional passing lanes in mountainous areas and usually only a few stop-controlled intersections outside the main urban areas.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A couple of busy intercity corridors outside Greater Vancouver feature more heavily signalized limited-mobility arterial highways that are mostly four-lane and often divided by portable median traffic barriers.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Highway 1 on Vancouver Island and Highway 97 through the Okanagan Valley are medium- to high-volume roadways with variable posted speeds that range from 50 km/h (31 mph) to maximums just slightly lower than the principal grade-separated highways.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Numerous traffic lights operate in place of interchanges on both arterials as long-term cost-cutting measures.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The building and maintenance of provincial highways is the responsibility of the British Columbia Ministry of Transportation and Infrastructure.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] There are only five major routes to the rest of Canada.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] There are also several highway crossings to the adjoining American states of Washington, Idaho, and Montana.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The longest highway is Highway 97, running 2,081 kilometres (1,293 mi) from the British Columbia-Washington border at Osoyoos north to Watson Lake, Yukon and which includes the British Columbia portion of the Alaska Highway.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Prior to 1979, surface public transit in the Vancouver and Victoria metropolitan areas was administered by BC Hydro, the provincially owned electricity utility.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Subsequently, the province established BC Transit to oversee and operate all municipal transportation systems.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 1998, the Greater Vancouver Transportation Authority, now TransLink, a separate authority for routes within the Metro Vancouver Regional District, was established.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some smaller island communities, such as Gabriola Island and, formerly, Pender Island operate routes independent of BC Transit or TransLink.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] BC Transit has recently expanded to provide intercity routes, particularly in the Northern region of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Other intercity routes were introduced connecting southern communities in preparation of the cancellation of Greyhound Canada's pullout from Western Canada, though options for intercity bus travel are still extremely limited.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Public transit in British Columbia consists mainly of diesel buses, although Vancouver is also serviced by a fleet of trolley buses.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Several experimental buses are being tested such as hybrid buses that have both gasoline and electric engines.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Additionally, there are CNG-fuelled buses being tested and used in Nanaimo and Kamloops systems.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia also tested a fleet of Hydrogen-fuelled buses for the Vancouver-Whistler Winter Olympics in 2010.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] TransLink operates SkyTrain, an automated metro system serving the cities of Vancouver, Burnaby, New Westminster, Surrey, Richmond, Coquitlam, and Port Moody.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2009, the Canada Line SkyTrain was completed, linking Vancouver International Airport and the city of Richmond to downtown Vancouver bringing the total to three operating metro lines.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A new extension to Coquitlam and Port Moody (the Evergreen Extension of the Millennium Line) was completed in December 2016.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Construction of an extension of the Millennium Line westwards through Vancouver to Arbutus Street began in February 2021, with future plans to extend the line farther west from Arbutus station to the University of British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Fare gates have been added to all existing stations, though in the past, SkyTrain used a proof of payment honour system.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In the capital city of Victoria, BC Transit and the provincial government's infrastructure ministry are working together to create a bus rapid transit from the Westshore communities to downtown Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In Kamloops, there is a bus rapid transit GPS trial underway to see how bus rapid transit affects smaller cities, rather than larger ones, like Victoria and Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Rail development expanded greatly in the decades after the Canadian Pacific Railway was completed, in 1885, and was the chief mode of long-distance surface transportation until the expansion and improvement of the provincial highways system began in the 1950s.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Two major routes through the Yellowhead Pass competed with the Canadian Pacific Railway – the Grand Trunk Pacific Railway, terminating at Prince Rupert, and the Canadian Northern Railway, terminating at Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The British Columbia Electric Railway provided rail services in Victoria and Vancouver between the nineteenth century and mid twentieth century.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Pacific Great Eastern line supplemented this service, providing a north–south route between interior resource communities and the coast.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Pacific Great Eastern (later known as British Columbia Railway and now owned by Canadian National Railway) connects Fort St James, Fort Nelson, and Tumbler Ridge with North Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The E&N Railway, rebranded as the Island Rail Corridor, formerly served the commercial and passenger train markets of Vancouver Island.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Vancouver Island was also host to the last logging railway in North America until its closure in 2017.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Current passenger services in British Columbia are limited.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Via Rail operates 10 long-distance trains per week on two lines.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Local services are limited to two regions, with TransLink providing rapid transit and commuter services in the Lower Mainland and by the Seton Lake Indian Band South of Lillooet with the Kaoham Shuttle.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Amtrak runs international passenger service between Vancouver, Seattle, and intermediate points.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Several heritage railways operate within the province, including the White Pass and Yukon Route that runs between Alaska and the Yukon via British Columbia.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] BC Ferries was established as a provincial crown corporation in 1960 to provide passenger and vehicle ferry service between Vancouver Island and the Lower Mainland as a cheaper and more reliable alternative to the service operated by the Canadian Pacific Railway and other private operators.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It now operates 25 routes among the islands of British Columbia, as well as between the islands and the mainland.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Ferry service to Washington is offered by the Washington State Ferries (between Sidney and Anacortes) and Black Ball Transport (between Victoria and Port Angeles, Washington).
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Ferry service over inland lakes and rivers is provided by the Ministry of Transportation and Infrastructure.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Various other coastal ferries are operated privately.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The SeaBus ferry connects Lonsdale Quay in the City of North Vancouver and Waterfront station in Vancouver.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Commercial ocean transport is of vital importance.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Major ports are at Vancouver, Roberts Bank (near Tsawwassen), Prince Rupert, and Victoria.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Vancouver, Victoria, and Prince Rupert are also major ports of call for cruise ships.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2007, a large maritime container port was opened in Prince Rupert with an inland sorting port in Prince George.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] There are over 200 airports throughout British Columbia, the major ones being the Vancouver International Airport, the Victoria International Airport, the Kelowna International Airport, and the Abbotsford International Airport, the first three of which each served over 1,000,000 passengers in 2005.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] As of 2017, Vancouver International Airport is the 2nd busiest airport in the country and the second biggest International Gateway on the west coast (after Los Angeles) with an estimated 26.4 million travellers passing through in 2019.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The earliest known visual art produced in the Pacific Northwest, and what would become British Columbia, was by First Nations such as the Coast Salish, Haida, Heiltsuk, and Tsimshian, among others.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Such Indigenous work comes particularly in the form of woodcarving, as seen in totem poles, transformation masks, and canoes, as well as textile arts like Chilkat weaving and button blankets.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Traditional Indigenous art of the Pacific Northwest is typically distinguished by the formline style, which is defined as "continuous, flowing, curvilinear lines that turn, swell and diminish in a prescribed manner.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Western styles and forms were introduced to the region through the establishment of British North American settlements in the late 18th century.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Notable English-Canadian artists of 19th and early 20th century British Columbia include architect Francis Rattenbury, designer James Blomfield, and painter Emily Carr.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Vancouver's art scene was dominated by lyrical abstraction and surrealist landscape painting in the mid-20th century through such artists as B.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Smith, Takao Tanabe, Don Jarvis, and Toni Onley.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In the following decades, the city would undergo more artistic diversification with the emergence of conceptual art, communication art, video art, and performance art.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Vancouver School of conceptual photography encompasses a cohort of Vancouver-based artists who gained notoriety in the 1980s.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] This school is generally considered to include artists Jeff Wall, Ian Wallace, Ken Lum, Roy Arden, Stan Douglas, and Rodney Graham.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Vancouver maintains roughly 350 works of outdoor public art.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some notable works include *A-maze-ing Laughter*, *Digital Orca*, *Girl in a Wetsuit*, *Angel of Victory*, *The Birds*, and the Brockton Point totem poles.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is home to the Vancouver Opera, the City Opera of Vancouver, Ballet BC, contemporary dance companies Holy Body Tattoo, Kidd Pivot, Mascall Dance Society, and butoh dance troupe Kokoro Dance.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It is also the home province for a plethora of independent theatre companies, including the Arts Club Theatre Company, the Shakespearean Bard on the Beach, and Theatre Under the Stars.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Performing arts venues include the Queen Elizabeth Theatre, the Orpheum Theatre, and the Royal Theatre, among others.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is the third largest music-producing province in Canada and the local music industry generates an estimated yearly revenue of $265 million.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The province is home to the Vancouver Symphony Orchestra, the Okanagan Symphony Orchestra, the Vancouver Metropolitan Orchestra, the Vancouver Youth Symphony Orchestra, the Richmond Delta Youth Orchestra, and the Victoria Symphony.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some important popular music acts include bands such as Spirit of the West, Theory of a Deadman, Trooper, Gob, and The New Pornographers, and solo artists such as Bryan Adams, Carly Rae Jepsen, Mac DeMarco, Michael Bublé, Nelly Furtado, and Diana Krall.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Music festivals in BC have included the Squamish Valley Music Festival, Shambhala Music Festival, and Pemberton Music Festival.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbian cuisine is commonly associated with healthy living, fusion, fresh local ingredients, and innovation.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] It can be divided into two broadly-defined traditions: cuisine associated with the west coast, which incorporates a variety of seafood elements, and cuisine associated with the interior of the province, which embraces local game meat, farm-to-table produce, and methods of curing and smoking.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Seafood is an important staple of the province's local food culture due to its proximity to the Pacific Ocean, as well as the region's numerous rivers and lakes.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] BC is known for several unique dishes and is a producer of fruit, wine, and cheese.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Seafoods of British Columbia include sushi (BC roll, dynamite roll, California roll), dungeness crab (boiled, tacos), spot prawns, wild pacific salmon (smoked, candied, teriyaki, chowder, sandwich), and halibut (baked, lemon ginger), as well as delicacies like white sturgeon caviar and geoduck.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is also home to numerous unique non-seafood culinary staples.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some dishes include borscht, Salt Spring Island lamb, Japadog street food, and Butter chicken pizza.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some unique pastries include apple cranberry cinnamon buns, Nanaimo bars, and Victoria creams.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia also produces several distinct local cheeses, such as kabritt, Castle Blue, and Comox Brie.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The London Fog tea latte was invented in Vancouver and remains a popular beverage among coffee shops in the Pacific Northwest and Western Canada; it is referred to as a "Vancouver Fog" in Scotland.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The Okanagan produces many unique fruits originating from the region, including Ambrosia and Spartan apples, Stella and Skeena cherries, and Corontation grapes.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Other fruits grown in the province include peaches, pears, plums, apricots, strawberries, blackberries, cranberries, and loganberries.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is renowned for its wine production.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The primary wine-producing regions include the Okanagan, the Similkameen Valley, Vancouver Island, the Gulf Islands, and the Fraser Valley.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] As of November 2014, there are 280 licensed grape wineries and 929 vineyards.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Given its varied mountainous terrain and its coasts, lakes, rivers, and forests, British Columbia has long been enjoyed for pursuits like hiking and camping, rock climbing and mountaineering, hunting and fishing.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Water sports, both motorized and non-motorized, are enjoyed in many places.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Sea kayaking opportunities abound on the British Columbia coast with its fjords.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Whitewater rafting and kayaking are popular on many inland rivers.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Sailing and sailboarding are widely enjoyed.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In winter, cross-country and telemark skiing are much enjoyed, and in recent decades high-quality downhill skiing has been developed in the Coast Mountain range and the Rockies, as well as in the southern areas of the Shuswap Highlands and the Columbia Mountains.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Snowboarding has mushroomed in popularity since the early 1990s.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The 2010 Winter Olympics downhill events were held in the Whistler Blackcomb area of the province, while the indoor events were conducted in the Vancouver area.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In Vancouver and Victoria (as well as some other cities), opportunities for joggers and bicyclists have been developed.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Cross-country bike touring has been popular since the ten-speed bike became available many years ago.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Since the advent of the more robust mountain bike, trails in more rugged and wild places have been developed for them.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A 2016 poll on global biking website Pinkbike rated BC as the top destination mountain bikers would like to ride.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Some of the province's retired rail beds have been converted and maintained for hiking, biking, and cross-country skiing.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Longboarding is also a popular activity because of the hilly geography of the region.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In certain areas, there are businesses, non-profit societies, or municipal governments dedicated to promoting ecotourism in their region.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A number of British Columbia farmers offer visitors to combine tourism with farm work, for example, through the WWOOF Canada program.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia is home to a comprehensive education system consisting of public schools and independent schools that is overseen by the provincial Ministry of Education.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The public school system is divided in 59 anglophone school districts and one francophone school district, the *Conseil scolaire francophone de la Colombie-Britannique,* which operates French-language public schools throughout the province.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] The anglophone school districts are governed by school board trustees who are directly elected by the school district's residents.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] A very small percentage (less than 1 percent) of students are home schooled.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Like most other provinces in Canada, education is compulsory from ages 6 to 16 (grades 1–10), although the vast majority of students remain in school until they graduate from high school (grade 12) at the age of 18.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In order to graduate with a graduation certificate, known as a Dogwood Diploma in BC, students must take a minimum of 80 course credits during grades 10 to 12.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] These credits include a variety of required courses (e.g. in language arts, social studies, mathematics, and science), as well as elective courses.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Academic achievement in British Columbia is relatively good, although it has been slipping in recent years by some measures.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In 2020, 86 percent of students in British Columbia graduated from high school within six years of entering grade 8.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] In September 2014, there were 11,000 international students in BC public K-12 schools and about 3,000 international students in other BC K-12 schools.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] British Columbia has a diverse array of higher educational institutions, ranging from publicly funded universities, colleges, and institutes, to private universities, colleges, seminaries, and career institutes.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Public institutions receive approximately half of their funding from grants from the provincial government, with the remaining revenue stemming from tuition charges and philanthropic donations.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Each post-secondary institution sets its own admission requirements, although the standard requirement is the completion of high school.
[src:british-columbia/british-columbia-p02] Two American universities (Fairleigh Dickinson University and Northeastern University) also have degree-granting campuses in Vancouver.
